## Overview

YOLOv8 relies on a structured set of metadata files that describe the dataset,
class labels, and file paths for training and validation. This report explores
each configuration file in the context of protein secondary structure detection.

---

## Directory Structure

```
protein_md_dataset/
├── dataset.yaml              ← Master config: classes, paths
├── train.txt                 ← List of absolute paths to training images
├── val.txt                   ← List of absolute paths to validation images
├── train/
│   ├── images/
│   │   ├── frame_0001.png   ← VMD-rendered protein frame
│   │   └── ...              (100 total)
│   └── labels/
│       ├── frame_0001.txt   ← YOLO annotation for that frame
│       └── ...
└── val/
    ├── images/              (40 frames)
    └── labels/              (40 annotation files)
```

---

## 1. `dataset.yaml` — Master Configuration

```yaml
# dataset.yaml — Protein Secondary Structure Detection
path: /home/user/protein_md_dataset    # absolute root path

train: train/images                    # relative → train images
val:   val/images                      # relative → val images
test:  test/images                     # optional test set

nc: 2                                  # number of classes
names:
  0: alpha_helix                       # helical coil (RED in VMD ribbon)
  1: beta_sheet                        # flat stranded region (YELLOW in VMD ribbon)
```

**What it reveals:**
- The number of detection classes (`nc: 2`) — tells the model output layer size
- The class index-to-name mapping — critical for reading prediction outputs
- The data split paths — YOLO uses these to load batches during training

